    "narrative": "For Ghost Ride the WHIP\u2019s May 3rd slate, our high-upside plays are anchored by **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Seiya Suzuki** (75.03). **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive +14% park adjustment and a prime spot in the #2 hole, making him our strongest play against Strider. Similarly, **Seiya Suzuki** enjoys a robust +18% adjustment due to the favorable matchup against Kelly and the benefit of a slow delivery from the opposing pitcher, which enhances his stolen base potential\u2014a critical factor given our aggressive pursuit of the category. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (64.77) and **Corbin Carroll** (63.44) also serve as high-floor, high-ceiling starters; **Vinnie Pasquantino** thrives with a significant +14% platoon advantage against Castillo, while **Corbin Carroll** maintains a strong score despite the defensive efficiency of Boyd, largely due to his premium batting order position.\n\nWe are navigating a few tactical risks today, most notably with **James Wood** (52.10) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (46.10). **James Wood** is starting primarily for his #1 order position, but he faces a tough 3.22 xERA arm in Henderson, suppressing his overall output. Meanwhile, **Cole Young** (42.74) stands out as the most difficult bench decision, narrowly missing the cut behind higher-efficiency options. While **Cole Young** possesses a solid profile, his projected output against Bubic was cannibalized by a negative park factor and his status as a lower-tier play compared to the established starters. We are currently holding **Trevor Story**, **Brice Turang**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Carson Williams**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Kyle Karros**, and **Luis Campusano** on the bench or unavailable, with **Max Muncy** remaining sidelined on the IL. Managers should keep a close watch on weather flags in stadiums with wind-out reports, as our secondary players like **Jose Caballero** and **Alex Freeland** are heavily reliant on those environmental bumps to stay viable in our daily Roto rotation.",
